{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is the handoff between request-construction logic and the API client payload. A unit test of a helper could miss wiring bugs where taxonomy labels are dropped before dispatch. Integration is sufficient with an in-process fake client capturing outbound payload. Rejected System because behavior text is about request content, not real network/OS/subprocess effects. Rejected Agentic/Workflow because correctness does not depend on model judgment or multi-step agent decisions.","test_description":"Wire classifier module + request builder + fake API client. Invoke classify() with a known taxonomy and assert captured outbound request includes the full taxonomy label set (no omissions, no substitutions) on every call path.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure appears at response handoff: API response parsing/adapter + taxonomy validation + return mapping. A pure unit test of normalization logic can miss bypass/miswiring in the module path. Integration catches that with a stubbed API response. Rejected System because no real HTTP behavior is required to reproduce invalid-label mapping. Rejected Agentic/Workflow because this behavior is deterministic mapping of a provided label, not model quality or chained agent steps.","test_description":"Use module with fake API client returning out-of-taxonomy labels (e.g., \"medical\"). Assert public classify() result is exactly \"unknown\" and raw unexpected label is never surfaced.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Behavior text explicitly isolates the normalization step and identical input/output determinism. Minimum boundary is one local function/object with no I/O. Rejected Integration because no module interaction is required by the stated behavior. Rejected higher levels since no OS/network/model call or multi-step agent flow is involved.","test_description":"Call normalization function repeatedly with the same raw response fixtures (case/whitespace variants already fixed in fixture) and assert deterministic identical final label each time.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.88,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior requires repeated live calls and consistency conditioned on provider outputs; correctness depends on real AI API behavior and potential model variability. Mocking would hide this class of failure. Rejected Workflow because only a single model-decision step per call is evaluated, not a multi-agent sequence. Rejected lower levels because behavior text explicitly says \"live API calls\" and consistency over real provider responses.","test_description":"Run N real classification calls for same document/taxonomy, record provider raw responses and final labels, and assert label changes only when provider response content changes (track drift rate threshold).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.14,"Agentic":0.78,"Workflow":0.04}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is interaction of budget config + tokenizer/counting component + dispatch gate. A unit test of one helper can miss policy application at module wiring time. Integration with faked client is enough. Rejected System because enforcement occurs before dispatch per behavior text; no real network/OS needed. Rejected Agentic/Workflow because no dependence on model output decisions.","test_description":"Compose classifier with real budget policy and tokenizer module, fake API client. Feed over-budget inputs and assert policy outcome (truncate or reject) happens before any client dispatch; within-budget inputs dispatch normally.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.4,"Integration":0.5,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This behavior depends on a real AI provider call and provider-reported token accounting; a mock can trivially pass while hiding real over-budget behavior. Although assertion is deterministic, execution path must traverse real model API. Rejected Workflow because it is a single call check, not multiple agentic decisions in sequence. Rejected Integration because behavior text explicitly relies on provider-reported live usage.","test_description":"Execute real API calls for representative documents with configured budget, capture provider usage metadata, and assert observed prompt/total token usage does not exceed budget for the defined typical-doc set.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.28,"Agentic":0.62,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Core failure is retry orchestration across modules (error classifier, backoff/wait policy, retry dispatcher). This is reproducible with a fake API returning rate-limit signals and controlled clock/sleeper. Rejected System because real network timing is not required to validate wait-and-retry control flow. Rejected Agentic/Workflow because behavior is infrastructure retry logic, not model-output quality or multi-agent decision chain.","test_description":"Use fake API sequence: first returns rate-limit signal, second returns success. Verify module performs wait/backoff call, retries correct number of times, and returns successful label instead of surfacing initial error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
